📺 Anime-Adaption 》1 Staffel bei Crunchyroll

📜 Beschreibung (Splitter Manga+)》
Nach einem tragischen Unfall, bei dem sie unter einer Bücherlawine begraben wurde, wacht Myne in einer fremden Welt auf. Plötzlich ist sie keine Collegestudentin mehr, sondern die Tochter eines Soldaten, fünf Jahre jung und leidet an einer mysteriösen Krankheit! Aber ihre Liebe zum Lesen ist ungebrochen… umso ärgerlicher, dass Bücher in dieser Fantasy-Welt extrem teuer und dem Adel vorbehalten sind. Was soll man bloß tun, wenn man unbedingt lesen will, aber keine Bücher finden kann? Selbst welche herstellen!

Das erste Kapitel von Mynes Quest, ihre neue Heimat mit Bücherliebe zu erfüllen!

I'm including this book on the thread not because I have anything particular to say about it (it was fine) but because of how I read it. «Shadow Ticket» is Thomas Pynchon’s latest novel. Yes, he's still alive and still writing. It's sort of a bridge between Against the Day (Lew Basnight makes a cameo) and Gravity's Rainbow (it ends with WWII about to boil over). It was fun to read because I like Pynchon but ultimately felt a bit light, more like a sketch for something longer than fully realized novel. But… like I said the real point is how I read it. Basically as a two person book club. Each week we read a few chapters and then met on a video call for an hour to talk about it. Partly, it's a nice way to read a book, especially something as dense and full of allusions as Pynchon. Mostly, it was a really nice way to hang out with a friend. We live an ocean apart (the hazard of being a diasporic rootless cosmopolitan like me) and staying in touch can be tough. I've started exchanging letters with some people but that doesn't work with everyone. With a good friend like this one, this kind of semi-structured weekly meet-up has been just a really really nice way to intentionally foster connection. We've already picked our next book to keep it going.

#bookstodon
